53:15.125 --> 53:16.394
"How could you say that?

53:16.494 --> 53:19.430
You're just trying
to get publicity."

53:19.530 --> 53:22.233
Milli Vanilli fans?
Oh, man.

53:22.333 --> 53:24.269
Death threats.

53:24.369 --> 53:29.474
"Your next show, this and this
is gonna happen to you."

53:29.574 --> 53:31.576
- The phone rang and
it was Charles Shaw.

53:31.676 --> 53:33.311
And I didn't know who he was,

53:33.411 --> 53:35.346
and he said, "I'm the real
singer of Milli Vanilli

53:35.446 --> 53:37.448
and you have to help me."

53:37.548 --> 53:39.484
So I called Sandy right away

53:39.584 --> 53:41.619
and I said, "I just got this
weird call from this guy.

53:41.719 --> 53:42.820
He says he's the real voice."

53:42.920 --> 53:46.324
"Ah, just a crazy person.
Just ignore it."

53:46.424 --> 53:49.093
- It didn't interest anybody.

53:49.994 --> 53:54.231
You get tired of trying to

53:54.332 --> 53:57.302
lead a jackass to water

53:57.402 --> 53:59.270
and make him drink it.

54:18.456 --> 54:21.726
[crowd cheering]

54:21.826 --> 54:23.928
- People wanted to believe

54:24.028 --> 54:25.696
they are really singing
these songs

54:25.796 --> 54:27.765
because it was
a good production.

54:27.865 --> 54:29.634
It was entertainment.

54:31.268 --> 54:34.038
- It's a magic trick pulled
off in front of you onstage,

54:34.138 --> 54:36.240
and the audience usually
wants to be deceived

54:36.341 --> 54:37.842
in a magic show.

54:37.942 --> 54:41.346
So if everyone benefits
from a scam like that,

54:41.446 --> 54:42.813
including the audience,

54:42.913 --> 54:45.516
it's very easy to
look the other way.

54:45.616 --> 54:46.751
- Everyone got his bonus,

54:46.851 --> 54:49.086
everyone was happy to be
successful,

54:49.186 --> 54:51.989
and the people are happy to
have this record.

54:52.089 --> 54:57.227
We all together were in
a very nice flow of success.

54:57.328 --> 55:00.164
["Money" playing]

55:00.264 --> 55:02.032
- * Mo-mo-mo-money rules
the world *

55:02.132 --> 55:04.001
* It's still
the same old greed *

55:04.101 --> 55:06.637
- Successful music is
a great money machine.

55:06.737 --> 55:09.139
- Their videos are hot,
their songs are hot.

55:09.239 --> 55:11.075
- Singles, albums,
maxi singles...

55:11.175 --> 55:12.309
- Buy it now.

55:12.410 --> 55:14.979
- The album made
$580 million.

55:15.079 --> 55:18.115
They had sold approximately
46 million records, global.

55:18.215 --> 55:20.284
There was merchandise,
keychains,

55:20.385 --> 55:21.519
ticket sales to the concerts.

55:21.619 --> 55:23.554
- It's Milli Vanilli.
Milli Vanilli!

55:23.654 --> 55:25.623
What a show. What a night.

55:25.723 --> 55:27.425
- We're going to
a Milli Vanilli concert.

55:27.525 --> 55:31.629
- They could've recorded
the alphabet, the phonebook.

55:31.729 --> 55:33.898
You name it,
they were selling it.

55:33.998 --> 55:35.199
- Their logo is
the running man

55:35.299 --> 55:38.135
and it symbolizes
the pursuit of success.

55:38.235 --> 55:39.937
If they do any better
next year,

55:40.037 --> 55:42.072
they're gonna have
to find a new logo.

55:42.172 --> 55:44.174
- At that time,
Frank Farian was worth

55:44.274 --> 55:45.943
almost half a billion.

55:46.043 --> 55:49.146
- * Money rules the world and
don't you love that cash? *

55:49.246 --> 55:51.649
- They continued to steamroll
through the end of the year.

55:51.749 --> 55:54.184
- And the winner is...
Milli Vanilli.

55:54.284 --> 55:55.720
- They won three
American Music Awards...

55:55.820 --> 55:57.354
- Milli Vanilli.

55:57.955 --> 55:59.624
- Milli Vanilli!

55:59.724 --> 56:01.659
- This train was moving.

56:01.759 --> 56:04.862
- Thank you to our producer,
Frank Farian,

56:04.962 --> 56:06.597
to our manager, Sandy Gallin.

56:06.697 --> 56:08.733
- We'd like to thank
Clive Davis.

56:08.833 --> 56:10.801
- * Money rules the world

56:10.901 --> 56:12.837
- Arista, BMG,

56:12.937 --> 56:16.441
they were cashing in
the bucks.

56:16.541 --> 56:18.008
- * Money, money

56:18.108 --> 56:19.910
- And the whole thing with
Milli Vanilli

56:20.010 --> 56:21.278
would have kept going if

56:21.378 --> 56:24.849
they had not been nominated
for the Grammys.

56:27.785 --> 56:30.187
- Well, because--
no, but, see,

56:30.287 --> 56:33.991
most everybody knew
the secret, and I didn't.

56:34.091 --> 56:35.560
They never told me this,

56:35.660 --> 56:38.663
so I just assumed they sang,
you know?

56:38.763 --> 56:40.164
[hip-hop music]

56:40.264 --> 56:43.000
So we're at a conference
meeting and I said,

56:43.100 --> 56:45.102
"I think Milli Vanilli could
get nominated for a Grammy."

56:45.202 --> 56:47.204
I thought "Blame It On
The Rain" was a Grammy song.

56:47.304 --> 56:49.273
They laughed at me and
they're like, "Trust me,

56:49.373 --> 56:52.543
Milli Vanilli's never gonna
get nominated for a Grammy."

56:52.643 --> 56:54.512
So I called
National Academy of

56:54.612 --> 56:56.046
Recording Arts and Sciences.

56:56.146 --> 56:57.815
They put me right through
to Mike Greene's office,

56:57.915 --> 57:00.417
the president of NARAS.

57:00.518 --> 57:03.353
I had no idea how somebody
actually does get nominated,

57:03.454 --> 57:05.355
and he said,
"Oh, you just put it on

57:05.456 --> 57:07.458
"your management company
letterhead,

57:07.558 --> 57:10.595
'please consider
Milli Vanilli for a Grammy.'"

57:10.695 --> 57:13.831
So I typed it up and faxed it
off to the Academy.

57:13.931 --> 57:16.233
Never thought another thing
about it.

57:16.333 --> 57:19.970
So when that ballot came out
and Milli Vanilli was on it,

57:20.070 --> 57:23.173
like, just everything
hit the fan.

57:23.273 --> 57:25.810
Clive called Sandy
and threw a hissy fit,

57:25.910 --> 57:28.546
and then Sandy called me
absolutely furious,

57:28.646 --> 57:30.648
like, "Look what you've done!"

57:30.748 --> 57:32.316
I'm like,

57:32.416 --> 57:34.552
"why doesn't anybody want them
to have a Grammy award?"

57:34.652 --> 57:37.655
[laughs]

57:37.755 --> 57:41.926
[suspicious music]

57:42.026 --> 57:44.995
- If Milli Vanilli had
been nominated for

57:45.095 --> 57:47.264
the lip-sync awards,
that would've been fine,

57:47.364 --> 57:51.902
but they got nominated for
this prestigious musical award

57:52.002 --> 57:53.938
and they were up against
people who produce music

57:54.038 --> 57:55.940
and write music and sing.

57:56.040 --> 57:57.407
They were up against
the Indigo Girls...

57:57.508 --> 58:01.646
- * Closer I am to fine

58:01.746 --> 58:03.614
- This incredible folk duo
who sang

58:03.714 --> 58:05.883
these beautiful, deep songs.

58:05.983 --> 58:07.017
[Tone Loc's
"Funky Cold Medina" playing]

58:07.117 --> 58:08.686
They were up against Tone Loc.

58:08.786 --> 58:10.320
- * Funky Cold Medina

58:10.420 --> 58:13.323
- Tone Loc made brilliantly
constructed records,

58:13.423 --> 58:16.026
full of incredibly clever
rhythmic artifice.

58:16.126 --> 58:18.128
- * Sweetness
- Neneh Cherry, who had

58:18.228 --> 58:21.231
a really interesting debut
album and had a lot to say.

58:21.331 --> 58:22.833
- * We always hang in
a buffalo stance *

58:22.933 --> 58:25.002
- * Back to life

58:25.102 --> 58:29.339
- Soul II Soul changed
the way R&B music sounded.

58:29.439 --> 58:31.976
They changed the way
music moved.

58:32.076 --> 58:34.912
- And so, if I'm one of those
artists,

58:35.012 --> 58:36.446
I'm like, "These guys?"

58:36.547 --> 58:39.249
*

58:39.349 --> 58:44.254
- We knew that the Grammys
were the highest standard.

58:44.354 --> 58:47.124
[resonant music]

58:47.224 --> 58:51.395
Then here we were,
you know, Rob and Fab.

58:51.495 --> 58:56.433
Not only that,
they want us to perform live.

58:56.533 --> 59:00.337
- I thought, how the hell are
they going to do the Grammys

59:00.437 --> 59:01.939
when it's all live?

59:06.443 --> 59:08.478
Live-sing.

59:21.091 --> 59:24.261
- Michael Greene was
the head of NARAS at the time.

59:24.361 --> 59:28.999
I remember taking a picture
with him, and him saying,

59:29.099 --> 59:31.802
"Be sure you do it right
tonight."

59:31.902 --> 59:33.904
- [whistles]

59:34.004 --> 59:36.140
Money, money, money
makes the world go 'round.

59:38.108 --> 59:43.447
[tense music]

59:43.547 --> 59:45.149
- We're at the Shrine.

59:45.249 --> 59:49.019
I remember getting out
of the car and going in.

59:49.119 --> 59:51.355
On that day, it was pressure.

59:51.455 --> 59:52.456
[applause]

59:52.556 --> 59:53.357
- Ladies and gentlemen,

59:53.457 --> 59:55.960
Mr. Mike Greene.
- Thank you.

59:56.060 --> 59:57.762
This is a great night
for music!

59:57.862 --> 59:59.429
[applause]

59:59.529 --> 01:00:01.298
- Yeah, boy!

01:00:01.398 --> 01:00:04.368
- All the stars are
in the building.

01:00:04.468 --> 01:00:06.503
- Woo-hoo!

01:00:07.838 --> 01:00:10.941
- Finally, it was our turn
to be on that stage.

01:00:11.041 --> 01:00:13.343
Cold sweat.
[whistles]

01:00:13.443 --> 01:00:15.012
- Well, girl,
you know it's true.

01:00:15.112 --> 01:00:18.215
It can only mean Milli Vanilli.

01:00:18.315 --> 01:00:21.585
[fanfare]

01:00:21.686 --> 01:00:23.120
- Hit it!

01:00:23.220 --> 01:00:26.223
["Girl You Know It's True"
playing]

01:00:26.323 --> 01:00:32.296
*

01:00:32.396 --> 01:00:34.598
- * I'm in love with you, girl,
'cause you're on my mind *

01:00:34.699 --> 01:00:37.134
* You're the one I think about
most every time *

01:00:37.234 --> 01:00:39.503
* And when you pack a smile
in everything you do *

01:00:39.603 --> 01:00:41.071
- Performing in front of
the Grammys

01:00:41.171 --> 01:00:44.308
with all those artists,
that was nerve wracking.

01:00:44.408 --> 01:00:47.812
- * And this is true
- * Girl, you know it's true

01:00:47.912 --> 01:00:51.716
- All those people who spent
years of their lives

01:00:51.816 --> 01:00:53.250
to get to this point,

01:00:53.350 --> 01:00:55.252
and we got here pretty fast.

01:00:55.352 --> 01:01:00.524
*

01:01:00.624 --> 01:01:03.593
[cheers and applause]

01:01:09.399 --> 01:01:11.535
- I remember sitting there,

01:01:11.635 --> 01:01:14.238
and I think the entire industry
knew at that time

01:01:14.338 --> 01:01:16.273
that it wasn't them singing.

01:01:16.373 --> 01:01:17.775
- [clears throat]
That was great.

01:01:17.875 --> 01:01:19.944
I was actually--I was supposed
to be in that number.

01:01:20.044 --> 01:01:22.312
I don't know what--
[laughter]

01:01:23.147 --> 01:01:25.049
- When he called out
the nominees,

01:01:25.149 --> 01:01:27.417
you know, it was like, "Man."

01:01:27.517 --> 01:01:29.319
- This year, the nominees for
Best New Artist

01:01:29.419 --> 01:01:31.789
are making all kinds of music.

01:01:31.889 --> 01:01:34.759
- Each one of them express
themself in a unique way

01:01:34.859 --> 01:01:37.027
that commands attention.

01:01:37.127 --> 01:01:40.164
- Now, the nominees for
Best New Artist are...

01:01:41.065 --> 01:01:43.734
- Do Rob and Fab
deserve the Grammy?

01:01:43.834 --> 01:01:45.669
- Neneh Cherry.

01:01:45.770 --> 01:01:47.838
- That's a tough one.

01:01:48.806 --> 01:01:50.975
We didn't sing on
the record, so...

01:01:51.075 --> 01:01:52.209
- Indigo Girls.

01:01:53.410 --> 01:01:54.644
- No.

01:01:55.412 --> 01:01:56.146
But...

01:01:56.246 --> 01:01:57.948
[tense music]

01:01:58.048 --> 01:01:59.483
[cheers and applause]

01:01:59.583 --> 01:02:00.818
- Milli Vanilli.

01:02:00.918 --> 01:02:03.754
- For the pain and everything
that we suffered...

01:02:03.854 --> 01:02:05.255
- Soul II Soul.

01:02:05.355 --> 01:02:07.825
- And the hard work that
we put into,

01:02:07.925 --> 01:02:09.159
do we deserve it?

01:02:09.259 --> 01:02:10.560
- Tone Loc.

01:02:10.660 --> 01:02:12.329
*

01:02:12.429 --> 01:02:16.066
- A very small part of me
says yes.

01:02:16.166 --> 01:02:18.002
*

01:02:18.102 --> 01:02:20.337
- And the Best New Artist is...

01:02:20.437 --> 01:02:23.407
- Rob and Fab deserved
the Grammy.

01:02:24.008 --> 01:02:25.075
- Milli Vanilli.

01:02:25.175 --> 01:02:30.247
[cheers and applause]

01:02:35.219 --> 01:02:36.720
"Oh, my God."

01:02:36.821 --> 01:02:39.756
Frank goes,
"Now, everybody's watching."

01:02:47.197 --> 01:02:50.300
[cheers and applause]

01:02:51.535 --> 01:02:53.203
- Uh, we want to say
thank you very much,

01:02:53.303 --> 01:02:55.940
but we want to say
there are a lot of artists

01:02:56.040 --> 01:02:57.607
here in this room,

01:02:57.707 --> 01:03:00.410
there are a lot of artists
outside in the world

01:03:00.510 --> 01:03:03.547
who could achieve the same
award that we achieved today,

01:03:03.647 --> 01:03:05.715
and it's an award for
all artists in the world.

01:03:05.816 --> 01:03:07.151
Thank you very much.

01:03:07.251 --> 01:03:08.718
[cheers and applause]

01:03:08.819 --> 01:03:11.255
- Thank you.

01:03:11.355 --> 01:03:13.257
- It was a joke
that went too far.

01:03:13.357 --> 01:03:16.326
And once they crossed
that line into

01:03:16.426 --> 01:03:20.497
something that
people really care about,

01:03:20.597 --> 01:03:23.667
that was the beginning of
the end for Rob and Fab.

01:03:25.335 --> 01:03:27.637
- Once they won the Grammy...

01:03:27.737 --> 01:03:30.140
*

01:03:30.240 --> 01:03:33.643
Once they won the Grammy,

01:03:33.743 --> 01:03:36.180
they hung they selves.

01:03:36.280 --> 01:03:39.783
[cheers fading]

01:03:42.386 --> 01:03:45.489
[mysterious music]

01:03:45.589 --> 01:03:49.459
*

01:03:49.559 --> 01:03:52.262
- The afterparty
for the Grammys,

01:03:52.362 --> 01:03:54.764
oh, man, we were already faded.

01:03:54.865 --> 01:03:59.469
*

01:03:59.569 --> 01:04:02.907
I remember having to listen
to Mr. Clive Davis.

01:04:03.007 --> 01:04:05.142
*

01:04:05.242 --> 01:04:07.411
We were so high

01:04:07.511 --> 01:04:09.279
that it took a lot of energy

01:04:09.379 --> 01:04:12.049
to just keep the stuff
together.

01:04:12.149 --> 01:04:14.818
*

01:04:14.919 --> 01:04:19.556
- Frankly, Rob and Fab didn't
do themselves any favors.

01:04:19.656 --> 01:04:21.892
*

01:04:21.992 --> 01:04:25.896
They were just acting arrogant
and, frankly, obnoxious.

01:04:39.676 --> 01:04:42.612
"I have no time.
Who's Paul McCartney?"

01:04:42.712 --> 01:04:45.449
[hip-hop music]

01:04:45.549 --> 01:04:49.553
- When they won,
Rob and Fab were way up here,

01:04:49.653 --> 01:04:51.821
these big stars that
just won a Grammy.

01:04:51.922 --> 01:04:52.990
And the bigger they got,

01:04:53.090 --> 01:04:55.692
the more celebrity
they became.

01:04:57.327 --> 01:04:59.529
They had to have Avión
in the limousine,

01:04:59.629 --> 01:05:01.365
sushi in the dressing room.

01:05:01.465 --> 01:05:04.168
- They wanted for nothing.

01:05:04.268 --> 01:05:06.803
- The stardom made them crazy.

01:05:06.903 --> 01:05:09.606
- Rob said, "Oh,
can you turn on my voice?"

01:05:09.706 --> 01:05:12.509
And Frank said,
"It's not your voice!"

01:05:12.609 --> 01:05:15.345
Believe it.
It's Brad Howell's voice.

01:05:15.445 --> 01:05:19.116
- He was singing with
my voice during playback

01:05:19.216 --> 01:05:21.251
and believing
that's his own voice.

01:05:21.351 --> 01:05:23.420
They were believing this.

01:05:23.520 --> 01:05:26.456
- They started to forget
the reality

01:05:26.556 --> 01:05:28.358
that they didn't sing.

01:05:28.458 --> 01:05:30.394
[tense music]

01:05:30.494 --> 01:05:31.895
- So they were doing
this interview one time

01:05:31.996 --> 01:05:33.630
and they said they were better
than The Beatles.

01:05:33.730 --> 01:05:38.435
*

01:05:38.535 --> 01:05:40.304
Think about waking up
every day and knowing that

01:05:40.404 --> 01:05:41.805
you don't sing
any of the vocals,

01:05:41.905 --> 01:05:43.640
and then saying you're better
than The Beatles.

01:05:43.740 --> 01:05:45.875
*

01:05:45.976 --> 01:05:48.578
I mean, that takes, like,
giant stones.

01:05:48.678 --> 01:05:52.082
You've really gotta believe
your own bullshit to say that.

01:05:52.182 --> 01:05:55.585
They got caught up in it.

01:05:55.685 --> 01:05:57.988
- At that point, they thought
they had the power,

01:05:58.088 --> 01:05:59.623
and they did, to some degree.

01:05:59.723 --> 01:06:02.159
They said, you know,
"We're in control now."

01:06:02.259 --> 01:06:04.428
*

01:06:04.528 --> 01:06:06.530
Millions and millions of
dollars were at stake

01:06:06.630 --> 01:06:09.899
and people depended on them.

01:06:10.000 --> 01:06:12.236
Frank depended on them.

01:06:12.336 --> 01:06:14.438
Clive depended on them.

01:06:14.538 --> 01:06:18.075
Everybody depended on
Milli Vanilli doing their job.

01:06:18.175 --> 01:06:20.110
*

01:06:20.210 --> 01:06:23.447
- Frank Farian was already
preparing album number two,

01:06:23.547 --> 01:06:25.149
"Keep On Running,"
and they wanted us

01:06:25.249 --> 01:06:31.488
to get back to Germany to go
promote the second album.

01:06:31.588 --> 01:06:35.859
But Rob and Fab were done.

01:06:35.959 --> 01:06:38.362
We wanted to sing.

01:06:38.462 --> 01:06:40.964
We wanted to come out
as singers.

01:06:41.065 --> 01:06:45.369
[soft dark music]

01:06:45.469 --> 01:06:49.273
- At Arista,
we had a weekly luncheon

01:06:49.373 --> 01:06:52.142
in the conference room.

01:06:52.242 --> 01:06:55.745
One day, Clive got a call and
he walked into the kitchen.

01:06:58.315 --> 01:07:00.050
And then came back out
and he goes,

01:07:00.150 --> 01:07:04.121
"They want to sing on
the second album."

01:07:04.221 --> 01:07:08.392
And I remember him saying,
"That's not gonna happen."

01:07:16.233 --> 01:07:18.535
"Oh, but I would like to sing."

01:07:18.635 --> 01:07:20.570
"Yeah, Rob, it's impossible.

01:07:20.670 --> 01:07:22.639
"You cannot sing and
Fab cannot sing,

01:07:22.739 --> 01:07:24.608
so please stop talking."

01:07:26.243 --> 01:07:30.580
- We couldn't continue
to be his marionette.

01:07:30.680 --> 01:07:32.782
Hey, listen.
[flaps lips]

01:07:32.882 --> 01:07:34.551
Done with this.

01:07:34.651 --> 01:07:37.187
So we started to lawyer up,

01:07:37.287 --> 01:07:39.389
and then that's when
we found out

01:07:39.489 --> 01:07:43.927
we signed a contract
for multiple albums.

01:07:44.027 --> 01:07:45.862
We had no clue.

01:07:45.962 --> 01:07:50.100
So to get out of under
the thumb of Frank Farian,

01:07:50.200 --> 01:07:53.002
we played a game
of cat and mouse.

01:07:53.103 --> 01:07:54.538
*

01:07:54.638 --> 01:07:58.041
Our MO was to hurt him.

01:07:58.142 --> 01:08:01.111
Let's push him to a brink
where he's gonna break,

01:08:01.211 --> 01:08:03.913
and then he's gonna say,
"You know what? I'm tired.

01:08:04.013 --> 01:08:05.915
Go away."

01:08:06.015 --> 01:08:07.551
You know, we didn't show up
to the video of

01:08:07.651 --> 01:08:09.653
"Keep On Running."

01:08:09.753 --> 01:08:13.323
And we told him,
"More money. More money."

01:08:13.423 --> 01:08:15.024
He's like,
"No, I'm not doing that!

01:08:15.125 --> 01:08:16.826
What else do you want?"

01:08:24.168 --> 01:08:27.237
They told Frank,
"If you don't give us 150,000,

01:08:27.337 --> 01:08:29.439
"we will go to the producer
and telling them that

01:08:29.539 --> 01:08:32.108
we are not the guys
who singing on the tape."

01:08:53.797 --> 01:08:56.800
["Girl I'm Gonna Miss You"
playing]

01:08:56.900 --> 01:09:02.506
*

01:09:02.606 --> 01:09:05.342
- The story broke in
"The Los Angeles Times"

01:09:05.442 --> 01:09:06.376
and all hell broke loose.

01:09:06.476 --> 01:09:12.916
*

01:09:16.686 --> 01:09:18.755
- Frank threw Rob and Fab
under the bus.

01:09:18.855 --> 01:09:22.492
- * I knew it from the start,
you would break my heart *

01:09:22.592 --> 01:09:25.762
* But still, I had to play
this painful part *

01:09:25.862 --> 01:09:28.265
* You wrapped me around
your little bitty finger *

